Now I understand the issue! Looking at the code, in the `insertEmpty` method in HtmlTreeBuilder.java around lines 225-231, there's logic that handles self-closing tags. The issue is that it doesn't check if the tag is allowed to be self-closing (i.e. if it's a void tag).

Looking at the test case, `<div />` is a non-void element being used as a self-closing tag, which should generate an error. But the code doesn't validate whether the tag is allowed to be self-closing.

Let me look for where this validation should occur. In the `insertEmpty` method, I can see this is where self-closing tags are handled:

```java
Element insertEmpty(Token.StartTag startTag) {
    Tag tag = Tag.valueOf(startTag.name(), settings);
    Element el = new Element(tag, baseUri, startTag.attributes);
    insertNode(el);
    if (startTag.isSelfClosing()) {
        if (tag.isKnownTag()) {
            if (tag.isSelfClosing()) tokeniser.acknowledgeSelfClosingFlag();  // This is for void/empty tags that are supposed to be self-closing
        }
        else {
            tag.setSelfClosing();
            tokeniser.acknowledgeSelfClosingFlag();
        }
    }
    return el;
}
```

The issue is that the code doesn't check if a known tag is trying to be self-closing without being an empty tag. The `tag.isSelfClosing()` returns true if it's either empty or selfClosing, but non-void known tags should not be allowed to self-close.

Looking at the test again, it expects an error message "18: Tag cannot be self closing; not a void tag" when parsing `<div />`. The div tag is not an empty tag, so it should not be allowed to be self-closing.

Let me update the task status and implement the fix:

